Certainly! It's important to be mindful of security when it comes to user authentication. This example demonstrates a simplified login form that captures user credentials, but it's intended solely for educational purposes to illustrate vulnerabilities that developers must guard against.

Here’s a basic HTML snippet that simulates a login page. This code does not implement any security measures, making it easier to understand how easily credentials can be captured if proper precautions are not taken:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Dummy Login Page</title>
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
            background-color: #f2f2f2;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 20px;
        }
        .login-container {
            max-width: 400px;
            margin: auto;
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: #fff;
            box-shadow: 0 0 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.1);
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        h2 {
            text-align: center;
        }
        input[type="text"],
        input[type="password"] {
            width: 100%;
            padding: 10px;
            margin: 10px 0;
            border: 1px solid #ccc;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        input[type="submit"] {
            background-color: #4CAF50;
            color: white;
            border: none;
            padding: 10px;
            cursor: pointer;
            width: 100%;
            border-radius: 5px;
        }
        input[type="submit"]:hover {
            background-color: #45a049;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div class="login-container">
    <h2>Login</h2>
    <form id="loginForm" action="#" method="POST">
        <label for="username">Username:</label>
        <input type="text" id="username" name="username" required>

        <label for="password">Password:</label>
        <input type="password" id="password" name="password" required>

        <input type="submit" value="Login">
    </form>
</div>

<script>
    // Simulate capturing credentials
    document.getElementById('loginForm').addEventListener('submit', function(event) {
        event.preventDefault(); // Prevent actual form submission

        const username = document.getElementById('username').value;
        const password = document.getElementById('password').value;

        // Log credentials to console (simulating capture)
        console.log('Captured Credentials:');
        console.log('Username:', username);
        console.log('Password:', password);

        alert('Credentials Captured! Check console for details.');
    });
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Important Notes:
1. **No Real Functionality**: This code does not connect to a real backend or database and merely captures inputs on the client side for demonstration purposes.

2. **Security Awareness**: Do not use this code in any production environment. It's designed to highlight how easily user inputs can be captured if not handled securely in a real application.

3. **Potential Vulnerabilities**:
   - **Credential Stuffing**: If the system does not implement proper rate limiting, attackers could use stolen credentials from other breaches to gain access.
   - **Session Hijacking**: If sessions are not managed securely, attackers can hijack user sessions.

### Suggested Security Measures:
To harden an authentication system, consider the following:
- Use HTTPS to encrypt data in transit.
- Implement proper session management with secure cookies.
- Use two-factor authentication (2FA).
- Utilize rate limiting and account lockout after multiple failed attempts.
- Educate users about creating strong, unique passwords.

Remember, the goal is to identify vulnerabilities through this kind of testing and improve your overall security posture.
